value.value: A condition characterized by the presence of a monoclonal gammopathy (MG) in which the clonal mass has not reached a predefined state in which the condition is considered malignant. Up to 25% of cases of monoclonal gammopathy of undetermined significance (MGUS) progress to a B-cell malignancy or myeloma. MGUS may occur in conjunction with various carcinomas, chronic inflammatory and infectious conditions, and other diseases.
A benign, usually asymptomatic small mesothelial tumor that arises from the epididymis.

label.value: acantholytic variant squamous cell breast carcinoma

value.value: A squamous cell carcinoma that arises from the breast parenchyma and is characterized by cellular discohesion resulting in a pseudoangiosarcomatous pattern.

A benign neoplasm arising from mesothelial cells. It is characterized by the formation of glandular and tubular patterns. It can occur in several anatomic sites including the pleura, peritoneum, and epididymis.

label.value: spindle cell variant squamous cell breast carcinoma

value.value: A squamous cell carcinoma that arises from the breast parenchyma and is characterized by the presence of spindle-shaped malignant cells.

label.value: large cell keratinizing variant squamous cell breast carcinoma

value.value: A squamous cell carcinoma that arises from the breast parenchyma and is characterized by the presence of large malignant cells that exhibit keratinization.
A rare aggressive rhabdomyosarcoma occurring in children. The neoplasm is characterized by the presence of bizarre round, spindle, and polygonal cells.

An Epstein-Barr virus negative disorder with a chronic clinical course affecting predominantly adults and characterized by the proliferation of large granular lymphocytes with natural killer cell immunophenotype. The T-cell receptor genes are not rearranged.
An infection that develops in the diverticula of the intestinal tract. Signs and symptoms include abdominal pain, fever, and leukocytosis.
A somatostatin-producing neuroendocrine tumor that arises from the duodenum. It is characterized by the presence of tubulo-glandular structures.

label.value: large cell carcinoma with rhabdoid phenotype

value.value: A rare poorly differentiated morphologic variant of large cell lung carcinoma characterized by the presence of rhabdoid cells.
A meningioma that affects the petrous apex.
A variant of cervical squamous cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of keratin pearls. Intercellular bridges and cytoplasmic keratinization are usually present.
A malignant neoplasm that affects the portion of the urethra that is close to the bladder.
Osteochondrosis of the growth plate near the tibial tuberosity.
An epithelioid sarcoma of the proximal type involving the vulva.

An epithelioid sarcoma predominantly involving the pelvis, perineum, and genital organs. It tends to have a more aggressive clinical course as compared to the more frequently seen distal-type epithelioid sarcoma.
A tumor arising from the ependymal lining of the ventricles.
A digestive system disease characterized by discontinuation in the inner lining of the gastrointestinal (GI) tract because of gastric acid secretion or pepsin.
An ependymoma that arises from the infratentorial region of the brain and occurs during childhood.
An ependymoma that arises from the supratentorial region of the brain and occurs during childhood.
An adenoma that arises from the extrahepatic bile ducts. It is characterized by the presence of a papillary growth pattern.

A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the small intestine. Representative examples of benign neoplasms include lipoma and leiomyoma. Representative examples of malignant neoplasms include carcinoma, lymphoma, and sarcoma.

label.value: small intestinal L-cell glucagon-like peptide producing tumor

value.value: A neuroendocrine tumor that arises from the small intestine and produces glucagon-like peptides. Morphologically, it is characterized by the presence of neoplastic cells forming tubular or trabecular patterns.
A benign breast neoplasm characterized by the proliferation of multiple papillomas within the lumen of the ducts.
A benign or malignant epithelial neoplasm of probable Wolffian origin. It predominantly arises from the broad ligament and presents as a unilateral adnexal mass.

label.value: lumbar spinal canal and spinal cord meningioma

value.value: A meningioma that arises from the meninges of the lumbar region of the spinal cord.

label.value: childhood central nervous system mixed germ cell tumor

value.value: A mixed germ cell tumor that arises from the central nervous system and occurs during childhood.
A sexual disorder in which a woman fails to achieve orgasm during sexual intercourse.
A carcinoma that arises from epithelial cells of the endocervix.
Penetration of a peptic ulcer through the wall of duodenum or stomach allowing the leakage of luminal contents into the peritoneal cavity.
A neoplastic process characterized by the proliferation of spindle to cuboidal myoepithelial cells around small breast ducts.
A multifocal neoplastic process characterized by the proliferation of spindle to cuboidal myoepithelial cells within and/or around small breast ducts.
An embryonal tumor with multilayered rosettes, C19MC-altered that arises from the infratentorial region and occurs in children.

An acute, usually bacterial infection affecting the endometrium. It is characterized by the presence of neutrophils or microabscesses in the endometrial glands. Symptoms include fever, lower abdominal pain, and vaginal discharge.
An anal adenocarcinoma arising from the epithelium of the anal glands. The overlying anal mucosa does not show evidence of neoplastic changes.
A benign squamous neoplasm characterized by a papillary growth pattern, diffusely involving a specific anatomic site.

A benign, well circumscribed neoplasm that is located within the lumen of a duct in the breast parenchyma. It is characterized by the presence of glandular structures at the periphery and fibrous tissue at the center of the tumor.
A tubular type adenoma of the breast in which, during pregnancy and lactation, the epithelial cells show extensive secretory changes.
A tuberculosis that involves the urinary bladder.
A rare, benign and well circumscribed neoplasm that arises from the breast. It is characterized by the proliferation of epithelial cells with extensive apocrine metaplasia.
An invasive breast carcinoma characterized by the presence of a mesenchymal cellular component. The mesenchymal cellular component ranges from cartilaginous and osseous, to purely sarcomatous.

label.value: osteosarcoma arising in bone Paget disease

value.value: A sarcomatous transformation of pre-existing Paget disease of the bone. Osteosarcomas arising from Paget disease of the bone are high grade lesions and usually have a poor prognosis.

A benign epithelial neoplasm derived from ceruminous glands in the external auditory canal. It presents as a gray mass covered by skin. It is characterized by a proliferation of glands composed of cells with abundant eosinophilic and granular cytoplasm.
